Headwaters at Incarnate Word, San Antonio
CHECKLIST COMMENTS: We had a nice group out for a bird walk at the Headwaters Sanctuary.  Christine Turnbull and Patty Pasztor were leaders.   The weather was cloudy during the walk with a light drizzle at the end.   Several birds were "heard only", including the White-eyed Vireo and Carolina Wren.  A few did spot the wren.  Some "flyovers" observed included a Great Egret, and several ducks.  It was an enjoyable morning.  Thanks to all for participating and contributing to citizen science at this beautiful sanctuary!

Some "flyovers" observed included a Great Egret, and several ducks.  It was an enjoyable morning.  Thanks to all for participating and contributing to citizen science at this beautiful sanctuary!

CHECKLIST COMMENTS: Took the dog on a late afternoon walk and happened upon a few migrants near the trail entry area as I was leaving.

LOCALITY: Headwaters at Incarnate Word, San Antonio
SPECIES COMMENTS: Blackish hawk with a yellow bill. He was perched in a tree with his prey which was a meadowlark. He stayed there for at least 30 minutes. We could see the band on the tail and the white and black on the interior of the wing. His eyes were very dark. It stormed earlier so maybe he got blown off course. I will add pictures.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Seen in the upper field near the northwest corner of the fence next to a pile of construction rocks.  It disappeared behind the rocks and then hopped on top of the rock pile and started bobbing.  Light gray with an eyebrow and a longish bill. Buffy coloring under the wings and flank area, and a whitish throat with faint streaks.  Very surprised to see it here!  Got good looks but didnt bring a camera today.  We were looking to the northwest from the Circle of Springs pollinator garden.
